{"id":"1901.02088","submitter":"Art Hobson","authors":"Art Hobson","title":"Realist Analysis of Six Controversial Quantum Issues","comments":"18 pages, 5 figures, 1 table","journal-ref":"Published in Mario Bunge: A Centenary Festschrift, edited by\n  Michael R. Matthews (Springer Nature Switzerland, 2019), pp. 329-348","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper presents a philosophically realistic analysis of quantization,\nfield-particle duality, superposition, entanglement, nonlocality, and\nmeasurement. These are logically related: Realistically understanding\nmeasurement depends on realistically understanding superposition, entanglement,\nand nonlocality; understanding these three depends on understanding\nfield-particle duality and quantization. This paper resolves all six, based on\na realistic view of standard quantum physics. It concludes that, for these\nissues, standard quantum physics is consistent with scientific practice since\nCopernicus: Nature exists on its own and science's goal is to understand its\noperating principles, which are independent of humans. Quantum theory need not\nbe regarded as merely the study of what humans can know about the microscopic\nworld, but can instead view it as the study of real quanta such as electrons,\nphotons, and atoms. This position has long been argued by Mario Bunge.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 7 Jan 2019 22:44:21 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 26 Jul 2019 21:10:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-07-30"}
